{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472847"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:01:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:01:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1557"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1557"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.21,0.07,0.33,0.37]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1557"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48922"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1557"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1557"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33922"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2128"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5369"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6210"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9201"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46861"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48922"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his mother. He has a three-day history of cough productive of clear sputum, runny nose, mild fever, and decreased food intake. He denies chest pain. He has no significant medical history, takes no regular medications, and has no known allergies. There have been no recent sick contacts. They live 10 minutes from the hospital. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears reactive but clings to his mother. His vital signs are: pulse rate 110/min, blood pressure 100/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, temperature 37.8\u00b0C, and SpO2 94%. His capillary refill time is less than two seconds. There is mild chest wall retraction without nasal flaring or suprasternal retraction. Auscultation reveals right lower zone crepitations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal a negative SARS-CoV-2 PCR. A chest X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti-viral therapy","Oral amoxicillin","Oral prednisolone and oxygen therapy","Admit overnight for observation and supportive management","Discharge for management at home"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a common viral lower respiratory tract infection (LRTI). The most appropriate management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Edischarge for management at home\u003C/strong\u003E. LRTIs are usually managed at home unless there are concerning symptoms such as decreased oxygen saturation (\u0026lt;90%), drowsiness, signs of dehydration, persistent vomiting, or severe shortness of breath. In this case, the boy is relatively well, and his oxygen saturation is only slightly below the normal range for children.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe chest X-ray shows peribronchial thickening, commonly seen with respiratory viruses. The heart is not enlarged, costophrenic recesses are clear, and the right heart border is clearly defined. Right lower lobe pneumonia would cause obliteration of the right hemi-diaphragm, and right middle lobe pneumonia would obscure the right heart border. There is no pleural effusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-viral therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this case. The patient\u0027s symptoms indicate a mild respiratory infection without severe complications. Viral respiratory illnesses are commonly self-limiting. Consideration for anti-viral therapy should be made in severe respiratory infections with multiple organ involvement (e.g., myocarditis).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmit overnight for observation and supportive management\u003C/strong\u003E is not required as the examination reveals a mild infection which can be safely managed at home, especially since the family lives close to the hospital.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral prednisolone and oxygen therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is the recommended treatment for acute asthma, which is an unlikely diagnosis in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral amoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended for suspected bacterial respiratory infections, which is unlikely in this case due to the patient\u0027s presentation and X-ray results.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Peribronchial thickening on chest X-ray is commonly seen with respiratory viruses.","Mild viral lower respiratory tract infections in children can often be safely managed at home.","Oxygen saturation below 90% in children with respiratory infections is a key indicator for hospital admission."],"references":["Wilson, E et al. Starship Guideline: Influenza. Retrieved from:  https://www.starship.org.nz/guidelines/influenza/ (viewed 17 May 2022).","The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Influenza. Clinical practice guidelines. Retrieved from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Influenza/ (Viewed 15 May 2022)","The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Viral illnesses. Fact Sheet - The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Retrieved from: https://www.rch.org.au/kidsinfo/fact_sheets/viral_illnesses/ (Viewed 17 May 2022)"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33922"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1557"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20057"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20057"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5f4da6cb-72e7-449a-8b65-4217751ed444.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5f4da6cb-72e7-449a-8b65-4217751ed444.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":459,"height":544}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33922"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-19T14:26:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-11T21:04:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1557"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48922"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"